<dl id="n41190b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n41" href="#n41190b">N41 (VI.B.33)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n41all.htm#n41190b"> 190(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <font face="wake">}</font> weeps for / <font face="wake">H</font>&apos;s soul</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Swedenborg had two simple retainers, Andersson and his wife, who acted respectively as his gardener and <mark>housekeeper</mark>. Because of the philosopher&apos;s non-attendance at Church, they were told: &ldquo;you ought not to serve in Swedenborg&apos;s house, for he is no Christian.&rdquo; Andersson&apos;s wife was very fond of the old man, however, and &ldquo;lay many a night <mark>weeping bitterly</mark> that the Assessor was not a Christian, and <mark>prayinq for the salvation of his soul</mark>.&rdquo; <small> George Trobridge, <a name="GTLS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#GTLS"><cite title="source">A Life of Emanuel Swedenborg</cite></a>, 2nd ed. (??) 333</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c06235g" href="c06all.htm#c06235g">VI.C.06:235(g)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
